ing to prove `5m < 2S.length`, perhaps we should instead aim to prove `m(m-1)/2 ≤ (S.length)*2`. \n\nBut then for `m = 5`, `m(m-1)/2 = 10`, and `S.length ≤ 5`, `10 ≤ 10` would hold for `S.length = 5`, no contradiction. \n\nHmm. \n\nActually, looking up again the Hajnal&Milner proof, the idea was to consider a graph where vertices are people and edges are calls, then:\n- The number of edges is `S.length`. \n- To fully connect the graph, we need `≥ m -1` edges, but this is not good enough. \n- They instead consider the sum of the degrees (each call adds 2 to the sum): `sum deg = 2S.length`. \n- Then they show that for all `i < m`, the first `i` vertices in some order have `sum deg ≥ i -1`, which eventually implies `sum deg ≥ (m -1) + m/2`, so `2S.length ≥ (3m -2)/2`, or `S.length ≥ (3m -2)/4`; but for `m = 5`, this gives `S.length ≥ 13/4`, i.e., `≥4`, which is not `≥6`. \n\nNot sure. \n\nAlternatively, the paper by Baker and Shostak says: \n\n\"For each call, we can assign a value to it equal to the number of new pieces of information that are learned by both participants.\" \n\nBut perhaps this isn't helpful here.",
